observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) and reconcile the balance against the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
Direct the Acting Municipal General Services Officer to maintain Property Cards for PPEs and incorporate the balance into the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
Direct the Acting Municipal General Services Officer to complete the disposal procedures of the unserviceable properties, in coordination with the Accounting Department, to derecognize the same in the books of the agency; and
Direct the Acting Municipal General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records, and that the Property Cards maintained by the Property Unit and the Property Ledger Cards maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct:
The Municipal Accountant and HRMO to expedite the reconciliation of records with PhilHealth to come up with the updated service records so that the full remittance of contributions to PhilHealth may be made;
The Municipal Accountant and HRMO to coordinate and identify the causes of non-remittance for the remaining balance of unremitted contributions so that appropriate action can be undertaken such as remitting the contributions and loan payments, and/or effect necessary adjustments in the books of accounts, whichever is applicable;
The Municipal Accountant to ensure that contributions are remitted on time and in full within the prescribed period pursuant to laws, rules and regulations; and
The HRMO to establish and enforce a policy ensuring the timely submission and processing of salaries and wages. This will facilitate the prompt withholding and remittance of mandatory contributions to the appropriate government agencies.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Direct the Local Development Council to specify the projects, programs and activities chargeable to the 20% Development Fund, and discontinue the practice of lump sum budgeting and inclusion of generic PPAs in the Annual Investment Plan and Annual Budget;
Require the Acting Municipal Budget Officer to secure approval from the Sangguniang Bayan before affixing signature in the Obligation Request for items stated in generic terms;
Ensure coordination among MEO, the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), Local Development Council and MPDC to ensure that procurement activities for PPAs charged to 20% Development Fund are properly planned, in accordance with DBM-DOF-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 1 dated November 4, 2020;
Assess the resources and facilities of the Municipality to evaluate full compliance with the requirements and conditions of the guidelines for projects by administration, as provided in Appendix 1 of RA 9184; and
Discontinue the practice of charging inappropriate/improper expenditures to the 20% Development Fund and strictly adhere to the provisions of DBM-DOF-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 1 dated November 4, 2020.

Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant to regularly conduct monthly reconciliation of the Cash in Bank records for all its bank accounts with the depository bank balances within 10 days from receipt of the bank statements and submit the BRS within the prescribed period attached with supporting documents such as subsidiary ledgers and complete copies of bank statements;

Require the Municipal Treasurer to submit and furnish the Acting Municipal Accountant of all paid DVs summarized in the Report of Checks Issued on a daily basis and copies of validated Deposit Slips summarized in the Report on Collections and Deposits to ensure timely recording of disbursements and deposits in the books;

Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to analyze the dormant bank accounts and communicate with the source agency to determine the nature and terms of the account. Further, reversion to the General Fund may be applied if proven that the unexpended amount is the balance of their counterpart. The management shall cause the closure of the dormant account and transfer the balance to an active account in order to protect the amount from the risk of loss of rights and ownership;

Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries for stale dated checks over 6 months to exclude them from the lists of outstanding checks; and

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to send written notices to the payees at least one month before the checks become stale and the cancelled checks shall be reported and attached to the RCI prepared at period of cancellation.

a.	Require the Accounting and Property Unit to conduct the required preliminary activities as provided in Section 6.1 of COA Circular No. 2020-006. The documents or reports gathered shall be submitted to the Inventory Committee as basis in the preparation of the Physical Inventory Plan;

Require the Inventory Committee to prepare the Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) and submit to COA the approved copy at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;

Direct the Inventory Committee (i) to conduct physical count of PPE by type and by department at the end of each year, and (ii) to submit RPCPPE, in conformity with the form in Annex 49 of MNGAS, to the Municipal Accountant Office, the MGSO, and the Audit Team;

Direct the Municipal General Services Office (i) to keep and maintain updated property cards for each class of PPE, and (ii) to reconcile with the ledger cards maintained by the Municipal Accountant;

Direct the coordination of the Municipal Accountant, MGSO, and the Inventory Committee to reconcile the physical inventory of the PPE with the ledger cards and the property cards; and

Direct the property unit to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) which shall serve as the basis for the dropping from the books and expedite the disposal of the unserviceable properties in accordance with existing rules and regulations.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the correcting entries for the erroneous reversion of uncollected Real Property Tax/ Special Education Tax Receivables at year-end and reconcile their records with the Municipal Treasurer for at least the last five (5) years. If warranted, secure link with the eTRACS for more efficient maintenance of accounting records on RPT/SET Receivables.

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and submit the updated certified list of taxpayers based on the Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s Index Card to the Acting Municipal Accountant at the end of each year;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to ensure that the amount of delinquent taxes is incorporated in the established receivable amount to be forwarded to the Acting Municipal Accountant.

Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to coordinate with the ECPAC Software provided to integrate in their system separate RAAOs of the 5% Calamity Fund;

Instruct the LDRRM Office to:

Prepare and submit to the Auditor monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF on or before the 15th day after the end of each month;

As much as possible, conduct LDRRM workshop/training/seminars within the territorial jurisdiction of the Municipality so as to minimize costs and save funds for other disaster relative activities; and

If possible, designate or re-appoint another qualified personnel to be the Chairman of the BAC, instead of the LDRRMO Head, so as to hit the target submission of documents in due time;

Terminate one (1) mobile phone line of the office upon expiration and end of the contract and consider the features of communication network of its free call/text to Smart/Globe. Also, make refund the unnecessary payments for double subscription;

Direct the Municipal Budget Officer, OIC – Municipal Accountant, and DRRM Officer to refrain from using the DRRMF for programs/projects/activities (PPAs) which are not directly related with pre-disaster preparedness, mitigation and rescue operations to ensure that it is utilized solely for approved DRRM-related PPAs.

Require the Head of the Human Resource Management Officer to compute the accumulated leave credits of the Master List of the LGU and to furnish a copy to the Accounting Office;

Require the Municipal Accountant to make necessary adjustments to record the Accrued Terminal Leave Benefits due to the employees; 

Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to annually appropriate for the accrued terminal leave benefits earned by each employee even on a staggered basis depending on the availability of funds; and

Maximize the revenue-raising power of the municipality to identify additional sources of revenue to fund the whole amount of leave benefits payable.

Ensure that the appropriation for EME in the Annual Budget is in compliance with the provisions prescribed in Section 325 (h) of RA No. 7160, and that the actual expenses sourced therefrom are within the limitation to avoid disallowance in audit;

Require the Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that the appropriation for EME or DF in the Annual Budget is presented under one-line item only which is the EME; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare correcting entries to reclassify expenses that were erroneously recorded to EME account.

Require the Municipal Health Officer and/or Acting Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking supporting documents to the Office of the Auditor that would be sufficient and relevant to establish the validity of the claims, and accordingly observe strict compliance on the basic documentary requirements under existing laws and regulations; 

Direct the SB to incorporate in their resolution the appropriate rate per medico-legal service rendered in accordance to the prescribed rules and regulations under Magna Carta Benefits for Public Health Workers (PHWs) and make resolutions that are consistent with existing laws and regulations;

Disburse government funds within the allotted annual budget and for the specific legal purpose it pertained with complete documentary requirements; 

Require the Acting Municipal Budget Officer to charge appropriate accounts based on the nature of transactions, specified conditions and purpose to ensure that obligations incurred will not exceed appropriation and shall be limited to the available allotment;

Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to ensure that all necessary supporting documents are attached before processing and approving payments, and refrain from erroneous charging of transactions to avoid overstatement and understatement of affected accounts presented in the financial statements; and 

Require all department heads to prepare a Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) in consonance with the budget to support the cost estimates of each department’s budget proposal and ensure that PPMPs shall include only programs, projects and activities crucial to the efficient discharge of its functions.

Formulate an internal policy for the processing and recording of financial transactions in the Municipality including submission of complete supporting documents by providing a timeline as to the submission thereof;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Acting Municipal Accountant to closely coordinate with each other in the processing and recording of financial transactions to prevent significant delay or lag in the process flow of documents;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant Designate to approve and process only those disbursement vouchers supported with complete and valid documentation and approvals; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to submit the above-mentioned reports within the prescribed period so that timely post-audit of transactions could be made and verification of the same could be facilitated.

Gather and process sex-disaggregated data and GAD-related information from its barangays and from various sources as identified in its GAD Code;

Consolidate the same for data processing, data analysis and data updating and maintenance of their GAD databases;

Institutionalize the GAD Database with adequate and systematically gathered sex-disaggregated data which will provide the bases for gender analysis, planning, budgeting, programming and policy formulation; 

Undertake gender analysis to identify and confirm existing gender issues and ensure that the programs, projects and activities are responsive to the said issues; and

Revisit Annex B of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01, which identifies the data requirements for specific gender issues.

Further, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive ensure that the GAD Focal Person should undergo trainings related to GAD to better equip him on the task at hand.

Direct the OIC - Municipal Accountant to maintain Supplies Ledger Cards for each type of supplies and other inventory items, to record acquisition, issuance and disposal thereof;

Instruct the General Services Officer to conduct a semestral physical count of inventory items by type and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to the Auditor concerned not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year and reconcile the results thereof with the inventory records maintained in the Accounting Office;

Require the General Services Officer to submit monthly the Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI) together with the RIS to the Accounting Office for recording purposes; and

Require the General Services Officer to maintain stock cards for each inventory to record receipts of deliveries, and issuances thereof.

Require the OIC -Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to review and check the completeness and proprietary of supporting documents before claims are processed for payment;

Ensure that the stated deficiencies are corrected in the succeeding payments to prevent suspensions and disallowances in the future;

Submit all lacking supporting documents as well as to ensure that vouchers and contracts together with all its integral parts forming part thereof be submitted;

Strictly comply with the provisions prescribed under P.D. No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001; and

Adhere to provisions of Section 62.2.3 of the Revised IRR of R.A 9184 and guarantee that procurement is effected in a manner most advantageous to the government in line with the principle of transparency, efficiency and economy.

Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), Technical Working Group (TWG), and BAC Secretariat to refund the amount in full so received in connection to the overpayment of allowance for lack of legal basis;

Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to stop the granting of monthly allowances to the BAC without legal basis and to strictly adhere to the rules and regulations relative to the granting of honoraria to government personnel involved in government procurement;

Require the BAC Secretariat to submit the lacking documents, that the reported number of successfully completed projects used in the computation thereof be supported with Notices of Awards, certifications that the procurement involves competitive bidding and other supporting documents; and

Direct the OIC - Municipal Accountant to ensure that granting of honoraria to all procurement personnel would depend on the number of successfully completed procurement projects considering the actual dates of issuance of the corresponding Notices of Awards in a given period. All claims should be attached with copies of Notices of Awards as basis for the computation of Honoraria in accordance with existing regulation.

Require the Market Supervisor in charge to conduct an inventory of the existing market stalls for rent, determine the existing lessees of the market stall and execute a yearly contract of lease embodied in a public instrument for every public market stall rental and follow the standards or guidelines provided under COA Circular No. 88-282A to ensure that the interests of lessees and lessors are protected, misunderstandings and ambiguities are avoided and peaceful operation of the public market in the Municipality is maintained;

Require the Municipality of Tubod, Lanao del Norte to formulate clear policies, rules and regulations, and administrative provisions pertaining to collections of market stall rental fees, computation, and imposition of surcharges, and other administrative matters affecting public market operations not mentioned in the Municipal Ordinance No. 267, S' 2018, amended by Municipal Ordinance No. 317, S' 2021, in order to attain full control over the conduct and operation of its own public market;

Require the Market Supervisor in charge to maintain updated records for the proper administration and monitoring of market operations. Reports should be submitted to the concerned officers for information or inputs for decision-making purposes;

Require the Market Supervisor in charge to prepare and submit Monthly Report of Collection starting CY 2022 to the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant for the proper performance monitoring and recording of receipts;

Require the Market Supervisor in charge to submit to the Audit Team and the Municipal Treasurer the updated and completely filled out Contract of Leases of stallholders as well incorporating in the contract the imposition of corresponding surcharges in cases of default payment starting CY 2022.

We recommended that the Management
Implement the provisions stated under COA Circular 2022-004 relative to the new PPE capitalization threshold of P50,000.00;
Implement the guidelines and procedures set forth under COA Circular 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of government agencies to address the discrepancies noted in the said account balances;
Direct the Acting General Services Officer to conduct complete physical count and classify properly the accounts presented in the RPCPPE;
Direct the Acting General Services to complete the disposal procedures of the unserviceable properties in coordination with the accounting department to derecognize the same in the books of the agency; and
Direct the coordination of the Municipal Accountant, MGSO, and the Inventory Committee to reconcile the physical inventory of the PPE with the ledger cards and the property cards;

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the implementing offices or departments to properly coordinate with source agencies to secure copies of agreements previously entered into in relation to funds received;
Direct and enjoin all department heads concerned to monitor the implementation of all projects funded by other National Government Agencies order to achieve the ultimate goals and objectives of the programs/projects/activities to which the fund was received, which is to promote general welfare and provide basic services to the constituents and furnish MOA, Trust Agreement, MOU or any document to the accounting office for proper recording;
Require to Acting Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the implementing units, to determine if the specific projects for which the funds were received have been implemented within the prescribed period. Ensure that liquidation reports were already submitted and received by the source agencies for proper adjustment in the books;
Require the Municipal Accountant to verify with the source agencies to determine whether to return or not the unexpended balance of the fund. If a return is necessary, direct the Municipal Treasurer to return/remit to the source agencies such remaining balance. Otherwise, file a request to the source agencies for the authority to transfer the unexpended balance to the General Fund as provided under COA Circular 2023-004 dated June 14, 2023, if the disposition thereof has not been provided in the MOA, Trust Agreement or MOU;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to conduct regular and periodic evaluation, analysis, and validation of the existence of fund transfers and take up necessary adjusting entries for the misclassified accounts, and address any issues on dormant or idle accounts;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to set up a control mechanism in the recording of the receipts and disbursements such as obtaining a copy of the MOA, Trust Agreement, MOU, or any form of agreement before processing any disbursements of the funds received from NGAs and other inter-agency transactions; and
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to update and reconcile the balances in their books and prepare the utilization reports for the implemented projects duly approved by the Local Chief Executive in order to establish the correct balance of the Due to NGAs account in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) and Municipal Engineer to, at the beginning of the year, submit to the Auditor the list of all ongoing government Programs/Projects/ Activities (PPAs) and those that are to be implemented during the year;
Require the Municipal Engineer to ensure that all programs, projects, and activities are provided with the prescribed tarpaulin signboards with updated project status to promote good governance thru transparency; and
Inform the Auditor within ten (10) days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted;
Ensure strict compliance with the general guidelines, reporting and monitoring of the information and publicity on Programs/Projects/Activities (PPAs) as imposed in COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 31, 2013, as amended by COA Circular No. 2015-006 dated August 20, 2015, and further amended by COA Circular No. 2016-003 dated August 16, 2016.

We recommended that the Municipal Vice Mayor and members of the SB:
Cease the granting of financial assistance to the constituents and concentrate on the legislative functions and mandated powers, duties under Section 447 of RA No. 7160;
Transfer the appropriation of Financial Assistance and Donations to the Executive Branch;
Omit the allocation for EME within the Office of the Sangguniang Bayan, as the discretionary fund is specifically designated for the exclusive use of the Local Chief Executive;

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Budget Officer to:
Charge the expenditures to its proper appropriation;
Annually appropriate funds for the accrued leave benefits earned by each employee even on a staggered basis depending on the availability of funds;
Ensure that all expenditures are covered with proper appropriations and that funds shall only be available exclusively for the specific purpose for which they have been appropriated; and
Stop the practice of obligating funds without a budget for it will render transactions illegal.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the HR personnel to review the paid leave credits monetization in CY 2023 and make adjustments, if applicable, to apply first the monetized SLs from available VLs of concerned employees;
Ensure that employees monetize first their earned VL credits before applying for monetization of the earned SL balances;
Make sure that monetization of more than 30 days in a given year may be allowed only for valid and justifiable reasons subject to the discretion of the agency head and the availability of funds but in no case should be more than fifty percent (50%) of the accumulated vacation and sick leave credits;
Check and review the correctness of earned leave credits and deductions made in the Leave Ledger Cards at the end of the year to ensure accuracy of the leave credit balance of each employee;
Stop the practice of allowing employees to monetize more than once during the year; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of CSC Omnibus Rules on Leave, particularly Sections 22 and 23 thereof.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Create a technical working group to facilitate the processing of the Certificate of Title of the 14 parcels of land owned by the Municipality in order to establish absolute ownership and protect the interest of the Municipality over its properties;
Provide additional personnel/support staff for the Acting Municipal Accountant to assist her in the analysis and reconciliation of PPE accounts;
Require the Municipal Assessor to trace/find the original title of lands owned by the Municipality as shown in the tax declaration and file the same;
Require the designated Municipal Budget Officer to appropriate budget for the registration/titling of the land owned by the Municipality;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to recognize in the books of account the unrecorded land properties of the Municipality, if any, and to maintain and update PPLCs for all the land owned by the Municipality;
Require the General Services Officer to maintain and update Property Cards for the parcels of land and other real properties owned by the Municipality; and
Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant, General Services Officer and Acting Municipal Assessor to reconcile their records pertaining to the parcels of land owned by the Municipality and effect the necessary adjustments to present the correct Land account balance.

Direct the OIC – Municipal Accountant to ensure that meals, snacks, catering services for special occasions, conferences, and committee meetings are duly supported with invitations stating the agenda of the meeting, activity design, guest lists, copy of program, attendance and minutes, and that funds have been appropriated for the purpose; 

Require the concerned offices to limit expenses for catering services/meals and snacks served during official meetings only up to the extent allowed under Section 343 of the Local Government Code of 1991, if the same cannot be avoided; and be reminded that the cost of meals and snacks spent for entertaining visitors/guests of offices concerned be charged to their monthly representation allowance which is the very purpose of such;

Instruct the concerned Office/Department to refrain from incurring meals and snacks during regular sessions as these are considered expenses incurred during the actual performance of their functions and not supportive of the mission and objectives of the Municipality, given that they were provided monthly groceries in their respective office;

Adhere strict compliance with provisions prescribed by Section 325(a) of RA No. 7160, Section 14 of Local Budget Circular No. 103 dated May 15, 2013 and Section 4.1 and 4.2 of Local Budget Circular No. 98 dated October 14, 2011;

Direct the Municipal Budget Officer and Local Finance Committee to perform a thorough review and evaluation of the budget, whether annual or supplemental, prior to its submission to the Sangguniang Bayan to ensure that all Personal Services items are properly identified and classified as PS and that appropriation for PS items shall not exceed the PS limitation at any point in time during the budget year; and

Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant to properly record the RATA and Quarters Allowance to proper personal services accounts in order to present the actual PS expenditures of the municipality and obtain the approval of the DBM from modifying one allotment class to another provided further that it shall not entail any increase in the total amount appropriated for an activity or project.

Prepare a Peace and Order and Safety Plan as basis for the allocation of fund of the Peace and Order Program and inclusion of the POP in the Annual Investment Plan of the Municipality where the amount of CF and/or IF will be based;

Prepare Physical and Financial Plan as well Accomplishment Report, and the submission of the report to the DILG be strictly adhered to in compliance with the provisions of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 dated January 8, 2015;

Revisit the guidelines set forth under COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 particularly on the identification of programs/projects chargeable to Peace and Order Program, COA Circular 97-002, and COA Circular 2012-001;

Disburse government funds within the allotted annual budget and for the specific legal purpose it pertained with complete documentary requirements and consistently adhering to the guidelines for the grant and liquidation thereof;

Submit complete documentation on the grant, utilization and liquidation of the funds released to the Local Chief Executive for POP that would be sufficient and relevant to establish the validity of the claims; and

Refrain from granting funds to elected officials and to other LGU personnel without complete documentary requirements.

Create an Inventory Committee composed of adequate members to be able to complete the physical inventory in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, dated January 31, 2020;

Direct the Inventory Committee to comply with the General and Procedural Guidelines as set forth in the same Circular to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability; and

Make needed journal entries to adjust the duly investigated reconciling items in order to reflect the accurate account balances in accordance with the same Circular and the Government Accounting Manual (GAM) for LGUs, Volume 1

Set-up and/ or update sex-disaggregated data or GAD database;

Integrate GAD PPAs in the regular activities of the LGU and administer the HGDG test on the PPAs, the result of which shall be the basis in the estimating the cost of gender mainstreaming and in the preparation of GPB; and

Prepare GPB and Accomplishment Report following the prescribed format in accordance with JMC No. 2016-01.

Recommendation
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the General Services Officer to submit the complete Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RCPPE) on or before January 31 of each year, copy furnished the COA Auditor concerned;
Require the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain Property Cards for each category of PPE accounts to substantiate the existence, completeness, and reliability of items composing the respective PPE accounts;
Require the General Services Officer to submit Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) to the Office of the Auditor and to regularly check the condition of the property and equipment. Any damage, obsolete and unserviceable property shall be reported in the IIRUP and immediately request for disposal;
Create an Appraisal Committee to evaluate the unserviceable properties, comply with the documents required, and recommend the applicable mode of disposal of the items in a Disposal Committee Resolution for the LCE’s approval and submit it to the Auditor concerned for evaluation and action thereon prior to the disposal of unserviceable items;
Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to reclassify the obsolete, non-functional, and those no longer used in the operation as shown in IIRUP if there’s any, from their respective asset account to Other Asset Account; and
Direct the GSO and Accounting Office to regularly reconcile their inventory records and review the composition of the PPE account to come up with an accurate classification of Property, Plant, and Equipment account balance.

Recommendation
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the OIC - Municipal Accountant to maintain Supplies Ledger Cards for each type of supplies and other inventory items, to record acquisition, issuance and disposal thereof;
Direct the OIC - Municipal Accountant to properly record the purchases of inventories in the appropriate account and the consumption thereof as an expense, upon receipt of the RSMIs;
Instruct the General Services Officer to conduct a semestral physical count of inventory items by type and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to the Auditor concerned not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year and reconcile the results thereof with the inventory records maintained in the Accounting Office;
Require the General Services Officer to submit monthly the Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI) together with the RIS to the Accounting Office for recording purposes; and
Require the General Services Officer to maintain stock cards for each inventory to record receipts of deliveries, and issuances thereof.

Recommendation
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to review and check completeness and propriety of supporting documents before claims are processed for payment;
Ensure that the stated deficiencies are corrected in the succeeding payments to prevent suspensions and disallowances in the future;
Submit all lacking supporting documents as well as to ensure that vouchers and contracts together with all its integral parts forming part thereof be submitted;
Strictly comply with the provisions prescribed under P.D No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001; and
Adhere to the provisions of Section 62.2.3 of the Revised IRR of R.A. 9184 and guarantee that procurement is effected in a manner most advantageous to the government in line with the principle of transparency, efficiency and economy.

Recommendation
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Ensure thru the Property/Supply Officer/ to accomplish the pre-repair inspection report after the conduct of pre-repair inspection of properties subjected for repairs and furnish a copy of this report to COA Auditor within five (5) days from the date of evaluation/inspection. Likewise, when the subject properties were already repaired, conduct immediately post-repair inspection and submit a report thereon;
Direct the Property/Supply Officer to attach the Certificate of Acceptance and Report of Waste Material duly approved by the LCE after preliminary inspection/evaluation has been made;
Direct the Accounting Officer to maintain a ledger card for the expenses incurred regarding repair and maintenance of every vehicle owned by the LGU in order to monitor whether the property is economically repairable or not; and
Direct the GSO to ensure that the damaged/replaced, unserviceable supplies and property were kept in a safe stockroom located within the premises of the Municipality awaiting for disposal thereof and disposed of in the manner prescribed by existing rules and regulations

Recommendation
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to ensure that payments for suppliers are made thru checks;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to attach supporting documents at the time of grant of cash advance;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to refrain or stop granting additional cash advances to officers and employees without liquidating first their previous cash advance;
Require the Special Disbursing Officer to return immediately any excess/unutilized cash advance upon liquidation, evidenced by an Official Receipt; and
Closely monitor the granting and liquidation of cash advance to ensure compliance with the aforecited provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002.

Recommendation
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer, Municipal Treasurer, and Municipal Accountant to disburse government funds within the allotted annual budget and for the specific legal purpose it pertained with complete documentary requirements and consistently adhering to the guidelines for the grant and liquidation thereof;
Submit complete documentation on the grant, utilization and liquidation of the funds released to the Local Chief Executive for POP that would be sufficient and relevant to establish the validity of the claims;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to refrain from granting funds to elected officials and to other LGU personnel without complete documentary requirements;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to record the transactions of the LGU following the generally accepted principles in accounting pursuant to Section 112 of P.D. No. 1445; and
Revisit the guidelines set forth under COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 particularly on the identification of programs/projects chargeable to Peace and Order Program, COA Circular 97-002, and COA Circular 2012-001.

Recommendation
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), Technical Working Group (TWG), and BAC Secretariat to refund the amount in full so received in connection to the overpayment of allowance for lack of legal basis;
Require the OIC – Municipal Accountant to stop the granting of monthly allowances to the BAC without legal basis and to strictly adhere to the rules and regulations relative to the granting of honoraria to government personnel involved in government procurement;
Require the BAC Secretariat to submit the lacking documents, that the reported number of successfully completed projects used in the computation thereof be supported with Notices of Awards, certifications that the procurement involves competitive bidding and other supporting documents;
Direct the OIC – Municipal Accountant to ensure that granting of honoraria to all procurement personnel would depend on the number of successfully completed procurement projects considering the actual dates of issuance of the corresponding Notices of Awards in a given period. All claims should be attached with copies of Notices of Award as basis for the computation of Honoraria in accordance with existing regulation.

Direct the Municipal Accountant and the personnel in the Accounting Office to properly coordinate and observe consistency and accuracy in recording financial transactions in accordance with the pertinent laws and regulations;

Direct the personnel in the Accounting Office to refrain from editing the accounting entries in the system without the consent of the Municipal Accountant; and 

Direct the Municipal Accountant to record appropriate accounting entries in accordance with the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:
Demand liquidation or reimbursement from concerned employees of their outstanding cash advances or require the accountable officer concerned to sign an authority to deduct their outstanding cash advances from their salaries or other emoluments due them until full settlement of their obligations;
Refrain from granting cash advances to officers and employees with unliquidated cash advances;
Strictly implement the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002.

The LCE to file the request for authority to write-off this long outstanding cash advances addressed to the COA, Audit Team Leader thru the Supervising Auditor.  No filing fee is required;
The Municipal Accountant to prepare all the supporting documents as required under Section Nos. 7.4 and 8.3 of the foregoing COA Circular; and
Seek legal remedy and consider filing of appropriate formal charges against the absconded accountable officer with unliquidated cash advances since 1993.

Back up all procurement with approved APP per approved budget by the Local School Board;
Procure commonly used supplies at the PS-DBM pursuant to the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulation of RA 9184; and
Attach complete supporting documents in all claims from the SEF.

We recommend that the Local Chief Executive:

Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) with coordination of the Municipal Engineer to submit at the beginning of the year  to the Auditor a list of all on-going government projects/programs/activities (“PPA”) and those that are to be implemented during the year as provided for in Section 2.1 of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2014. Likewise, maintain and submit a Monthly Monitoring Report on the Project Status every 3rd day of the following month;

Direct the BAC to require the winning bidder to post performance security within the period as stipulated in the Notice of Award and prior to the signing of the contract in adherence to Section 39.1 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184;

